const faqs = [
  { q: "Do I need a license to Airbnb in Barrie, Ontario?", a: "No. As of April 2026, Barrie has no short-term rental license, no registration process, and no permit requirement. You can list your property on Airbnb, VRBO, or Booking.com without any municipal approval. City staff are investigating regulatory options under Council Motion 24-G-033, but no bylaw has been passed. General property standards, noise, and parking bylaws still apply." },
  { q: "Can I Airbnb an investment property in Barrie?", a: "Yes. Barrie has no principal residence requirement. You can operate a short-term rental on an investment property, a secondary home, a cottage, or your primary residence. This is a significant advantage over Toronto, Mississauga, and most other GTA cities where STRs are restricted to where you actually live." },
  { q: "What is the STR night limit in Barrie?", a: "There is no night limit. You can host guests 365 nights a year in Barrie. Compare that to Toronto (180 nights for entire home rentals), Oshawa (180 days), and Milton (180 days). Barrie is one of the last major Ontario cities with zero regulatory limits on STR operation." },
  { q: "Does Barrie have an MAT (Municipal Accommodation Tax)?", a: "No. As of April 2026, Barrie does not charge a Municipal Accommodation Tax on short-term rentals. This is another financial advantage over cities like Toronto (8.5% MAT), Ottawa (4%), and Oshawa (5%). HST (13%) still applies federally if your annual STR revenue exceeds $30,000." },
  { q: "How many Airbnbs are there in Barrie?", a: "According to the Ontario Ministry of Tourism, Culture and Sport, Barrie had 503 active short-term rental listings as of December 2024. That number is likely higher in 2026 given ongoing tourism growth. With no regulatory friction, the market has expanded faster than most comparable Ontario cities." },
  { q: "Is Barrie going to regulate Airbnbs?", a: "Probably. Barrie City Council adopted Motion 24-G-033 directing staff to investigate STR regulation. Staff identified four possible approaches: a zoning bylaw, a business licensing bylaw, a fees bylaw, or a dedicated STR bylaw. Council is currently leaning toward a complaint-based enforcement model because it is cheaper to administer than full licensing. Most industry watchers expect regulation within 12 to 24 months." },
  { q: "What rules apply to Airbnbs in Barrie right now?", a: "General municipal bylaws still apply: property standards, noise (excessive noise prohibited 11pm to 7am), parking, waste collection, and fire code. Your building must have working smoke alarms and carbon monoxide detectors. Ontario Building Code applies to any renovations. Condo corporations can also prohibit STRs even though the city does not." },
